2040 PLAN

Residents Going Solar in Minneapolis: Cost Analysis

  • On average, Minneapolis residents spend $156 per month on electricity and $1,872 per year
  • The average electric rates in Minneapolis cost 16 ¢/kWh
  • Therefore the average electricity customer in Minneapolis is using 955 kWh of electricity per month, and 11,460 kWh yearly
 
  • Solar panel system size: 7.75 kW DC
  • Average solar panel cost: $3.43/W
  • Average cost of solar system (size 7.75 kW DC): $26,583
  • Net payback period: 18 years
READ MORE

In evaluating the cost of energy programs, it is important to maintain this focus on affordable energy

Median Household Income (2021): $70,099

Persons in Poverty (2021): 17%

 

–Breakdown the different cost and financing options

  1. Minneapolis Green Cost Share Program: This city-run program provides financial assistance for businesses and homeowners interested in installing solar panels or other renewable energy systems.

  2. City Rebates: The city offers rebates and incentives to help offset the cost of installation and has streamlined the permitting process to make it easier for property owners to install solar panels.

  3. Federal Tax Credit: The federal government offers a tax credit for solar installations equal to 26% of the total cost of the system. This credit is available for residential and commercial solar installations.

  4. Made in Minnesota Solar Incentive Program: The Minnesota Department of Commerce offers cash incentives for solar installations under its Made in Minnesota Solar Incentive Program. The program provides incentives for solar panels manufactured in Minnesota and can provide up to $0.20 per kilowatt-hour produced by the system.Property Tax Exemption: The City of Minneapolis offers a property tax exemption for solar installations. Under the exemption, the value of the solar system is not included in the property’s assessed value for tax purposes.

  5. Xcel Energy Solar*Rewards Program: Xcel Energy, one of the two electric utilities serving Minneapolis, offers rebates for residential and commercial solar installations through its Solar*Rewards Program. The rebates vary depending on the size of the system and can be up to $4,500 for residential installations and up to $50,000 for commercial installations.

  6. Energy Efficiency Loans: The City of Minneapolis offers energy efficiency loans through its Home Energy Loan Program (HELP) and the Commercial Property Assessed Clean Energy (PACE) program. These loans can be used to finance solar installations and other energy efficiency upgrades.

  7.

So, I was doing some research on solar energy and stumbled upon a really interesting case study about the cost of installing solar panels in Minnesota. Apparently, the average cost for a 5 kW solar panel system in the state ranges from $14,578 to $19,722, with the overall average coming out to be $17,150.

Now, I know that might sound like a lot of money, but hear me out. The cost of solar energy has actually decreased significantly over the years, and with the right incentives and financing options, it can actually be a very affordable and realistic option for homeowners and businesses in Minneapolis. Plus, the long-term savings on energy bills can really add up over time. So, if you're looking to make the switch to renewable energy, don't let the initial sticker shock scare you away. It might just be worth it in the long run!

 

Even if onsite solar doesn’t make sense for you, you can still participate in the clean energy transition and save on your electric bills by subscribing to a community solar farm. Community solar programs in Minneapolis, MN typically save you 5-15% in electricity costs over the course of the year. For the average electricity customer in Minneapolis, MN, 10% annual savings would amount to $187 in savings per year.

Residents Going Solar in Minneapolis: Cost Analysis

  • On average, Minneapolis residents spend $156 per month on electricity and $1,872 per year
  • The average electric rates in Minneapolis cost 16 ¢/kWh
  • Therefore the average electricity customer in Minneapolis is using 955 kWh of electricity per month, and 11,460 kWh yearly
 
  • Solar panel system size: 7.75 kW DC
  • Average solar panel cost: $3.43/W
  • Average cost of solar system (size 7.75 kW DC): $26,583
  • Net payback period: 18 years
READ MORE

In evaluating the cost of energy programs, it is important to maintain this focus on affordable energy

Median Household Income (2021): $70,099

Persons in Poverty (2021): 17%

 

-Breakdown the different cost and financing options

  1. Minneapolis Green Cost Share Program: This city-run program provides financial assistance for businesses and homeowners interested in installing solar panels or other renewable energy systems.

  2. City Rebates: The city offers rebates and incentives to help offset the cost of installation and has streamlined the permitting process to make it easier for property owners to install solar panels.

  3. Federal Tax Credit: The federal government offers a tax credit for solar installations equal to 26% of the total cost of the system. This credit is available for residential and commercial solar installations.

  4. Made in Minnesota Solar Incentive Program: The Minnesota Department of Commerce offers cash incentives for solar installations under its Made in Minnesota Solar Incentive Program. The program provides incentives for solar panels manufactured in Minnesota and can provide up to $0.20 per kilowatt-hour produced by the system.Property Tax Exemption: The City of Minneapolis offers a property tax exemption for solar installations. Under the exemption, the value of the solar system is not included in the property's assessed value for tax purposes.

  5. Xcel Energy Solar*Rewards Program: Xcel Energy, one of the two electric utilities serving Minneapolis, offers rebates for residential and commercial solar installations through its Solar*Rewards Program. The rebates vary depending on the size of the system and can be up to $4,500 for residential installations and up to $50,000 for commercial installations.

  6. Energy Efficiency Loans: The City of Minneapolis offers energy efficiency loans through its Home Energy Loan Program (HELP) and the Commercial Property Assessed Clean Energy (PACE) program. These loans can be used to finance solar installations and other energy efficiency upgrades.

  7.

      Our vision

      Our vision for Minneapolis 2040 is to create a city that is sustainable, affordable and equitable for all. We believe that solar energy is a key component of achieving this vision, and we are dedicated to finding practical and realistic ways to implement it. By working together, we can create a brighter future for Minneapolis and for the planet.

        Solar energy is forecasted to contribute the smallest percentage of renewable energy

        This is an example page. It's different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:

        Hi there! I'm a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my website. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like piña coladas. (And gettin' caught in the rain.)

        ...or something like this:

        The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickeys to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.

        As a new WordPress user, you should go to your dashboard to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!

        ]]>         2 0 0 0         <![CDATA[Privacy Policy]]> https://optimum-stinkbug.10web.site/?page_id=3 Sun, 23 Apr 2023 03:34:05 +0000 https://optimum-stinkbug.10web.site/?page_id=3

        Who we are

        Suggested text: Our website address is: https://optimum-stinkbug.10web.site.

        Comments

        Suggested text: When visitors leave comments on the site we collect the data shown in the comments form, and also the visitor’s IP address and browser user agent string to help spam detection.

        An anonymized string created from your email address (also called a hash) may be provided to the Gravatar service to see if you are using it. The Gravatar service privacy policy is available here: https://automattic.com/privacy/. After approval of your comment, your profile picture is visible to the public in the context of your comment.

        Media

        Suggested text: If you upload images to the website, you should avoid uploading images with embedded location data (EXIF GPS) included. Visitors to the website can download and extract any location data from images on the website.

        Cookies

        Suggested text: If you leave a comment on our site you may opt-in to saving your name, email address and website in cookies. These are for your convenience so that you do not have to fill in your details again when you leave another comment. These cookies will last for one year.

        If you visit our login page, we will set a temporary cookie to determine if your browser accepts cookies. This cookie contains no personal data and is discarded when you close your browser.

        When you log in, we will also set up several cookies to save your login information and your screen display choices. Login cookies last for two days, and screen options cookies last for a year. If you select "Remember Me", your login will persist for two weeks. If you log out of your account, the login cookies will be removed.

        If you edit or publish an article, an additional cookie will be saved in your browser. This cookie includes no personal data and simply indicates the post ID of the article you just edited. It expires after 1 day.

        Embedded content from other websites

        Suggested text: Articles on this site may include embedded content (e.g. videos, images, articles, etc.). Embedded content from other websites behaves in the exact same way as if the visitor has visited the other website.

        These websites may collect data about you, use cookies, embed additional third-party tracking, and monitor your interaction with that embedded content, including tracking your interaction with the embedded content if you have an account and are logged in to that website.

        Who we share your data with

        Suggested text: If you request a password reset, your IP address will be included in the reset email.

        How long we retain your data

        Suggested text: If you leave a comment, the comment and its metadata are retained indefinitely. This is so we can recognize and approve any follow-up comments automatically instead of holding them in a moderation queue.

        For users that register on our website (if any), we also store the personal information they provide in their user profile. All users can see, edit, or delete their personal information at any time (except they cannot change their username). Website administrators can also see and edit that information.

        What rights you have over your data

        Suggested text: If you have an account on this site, or have left comments, you can request to receive an exported file of the personal data we hold about you, including any data you have provided to us. You can also request that we erase any personal data we hold about you. This does not include any data we are obliged to keep for administrative, legal, or security purposes.

        Where your data is sent

        Suggested text: Visitor comments may be checked through an automated spam detection service.

                                      HIMinneapolis Energy Goals

                                      Minneapolis 2040 Plan Implementation helps Minneapolis create a more sustainable future. By assessing potential solar implementation strategies with an additional focus on economic strategies, the 2040 plan is more transparent and achievable. Follow one of our suggested plans for a greener tomorrow!

                                       See Plans

                                      2040 Plan Goals

                                      Our Solar Focused Plan Goals

                                      Renewable goals for Minneapolis Communities

                                      The 2040 plan requires Minneapolis to have 100% renewable energy and an 80% reduction of GHG emissions by 2040.

                                      Solar energy is forecasted to contribute the smallest percentage of renewable energy 

                                      This plan identifies opportunities for solar energy utilization to be maximized in Minneapolis's residential energy sector. Ultimately, contributing a bigger role to the 100% renewable energy goal for 2040 by relying completely on in-house generation. 

                                      Community Engagement

                                      The Minneapolis 2040 plan emphasizes the importance of engaging the community in the transition to clean energy. The city will work with local organizations and businesses to promote energy conservation and efficiency, as well as to raise awareness about the benefits of renewable energy.

                                      Affordable Energy

                                      The city's plan emphasizes the importance of supporting renewable energy. Our plan works with businesses and homeowners to promote affordable solar energy by compiling several incentives and rebates available for solar installations.

                                      What's 2040 Missing?

                                      Switching to solar energy for a big city can be a complex and challenging task due to several factors, including:

                                      •  Citizen buy-in
                                      • Space limitations
                                      • Affordability
                                      • Equitable access                                                                                                     
                                      • Energy storage
                                      • Grid infrastructure
                                      • Intermittency of solar power
                                      • Regulatory hurdles

                                      Start with Energy

                                      Energy Breakdown
                                      Team story

                                      Inspiration struck a cohort of Minneapolis scholars upon reading the city's landmark 2040 plan, compelling them to take action towards achieving its objectives. They harbored a keen interest in renewable energy with an emphasis on harnessing solar power that could be easily accessible and practical for all. Meticulous effort went into crafting an informative and up-to-date web page as means of disseminating knowledge and instilling enthusiasm among others about solar energy's potential.

                                      Subscribe to newsletter

                                      Enter your email address to register to our newsletter subscription!

                                        HOW?

                                        Recommendations for the City of Minneapolis to implement into the 2040 plan to maximize the amount of renewable energy from solar

                                        Neighborhood organization ↗

                                        Neighborhood organizations in Minneapolis can work with local utilities and community solar programs to access solar energy. The City of Minneapolis has a community solar garden program that allows residents and businesses to subscribe to solar energy systems in their area. See for more information on the cost and financing options for community solar programs.

                                        City↗

                                        The City of Minneapolis has several initiatives to promote solar energy adoption, including a solar energy system for its municipal buildings. See for more information on the cost and financing options for the municipal solar energy system.

                                        Municipal ↗

                                        Municipalities in Minneapolis can work with local utilities to install solar energy systems and access incentives and financing options. For example, Xcel Energy, the main electric utility provider in Minneapolis, offers a Solar*Rewards program that provides incentives for solar energy installation. See for more information on the cost and financing options for municipal solar energy systems.

                                        Private organization ↗

                                        Private organizations in Minneapolis can access various incentives and financing options to install solar energy systems. The Minnesota Department of Commerce provides a list of incentives and financing programs for solar energy installation in the state, which private organizations can access. See for local solar energy installation companies, cost estimates and financing options.

                                        Neighborhood Organizations

                                        The percentage of Minneapolis communitywide electricity use from local and directly purchased renewable energy has declined in recent years, but the cost of wind and solar energy is rapidly falling, and a number of alternative approaches like community solar are making renewable electricity easier to access.

                                        Community Solar

                                        • The city's high solar capacity provided a good basis for the state’s community solar program which generate around 44MW
                                        • Community solar options have increasingly flexible terms, and they’re a great option for renters who want to go solar as opposed to homeowners who may benefit from rooftop panels.
                                        • For most communities, the rooftop generation potential is equivalent to between 30% and 60% of the community’s total electric energy consumption
                                          • Largest impact given there are 83 residential neighborhood blocks in Minneapolis and 70 neighborhood organizations

                                        This plan provides a way to identify neighborhoods where community solar can be a solution for population with limited access to rooftop solar

                                        City Housing Characteristics

                                        Alternatives to owning solar (MN gov)

                                        If purchasing your own solar energy system isn’t an option, consider the following opportunities as a way to support solar and clean energy.

                                          • Subscribe to a community solar garden: An emerging option for the customers of several Minneapolis electric utilities customers is joining a community solar garden, these solar photovoltaic systems provide electricity to participating subscribers. They are a way for people in Minneapolis to get at least a portion of their power from solar electric systems without installing their own stand-alone project. 

                                          • Information on Community Solar Gardens.

                                        City

                                        The city can maximize the amount of solar generation on City-owned facilities such as the Water Treatment reservoirs and large City-owned buildings. There will be an 11 year payback period for each array, but over the 25 year life of an array, the savings will have a net present value of twice the initial cost of the arrays.

                                        One of the ways that Minneapolis can reach these goals is by utilizing the untapped resource of commercial and industrial (C&I)
                                        rooftops for solar photovoltaic (PV) arrays.

                                         

                                        ACTION STEPS

                                        The City will seek to accomplish the following action steps to encourage the use and generation of renewable and carbon-free energy in the city.

                                        1. Invest in grid modernization to accommodate increases in distributed renewable energy generation.
                                        2. Purchase clean energy directly through community solar gardens, contracts with renewable electricity developers, utility offerings, or by installing renewable energy systems on municipal buildings.
                                        3. Continue to support and advocate for accelerated and deeper decarbonization of electricity supplied by Xcel Energy.
                                        4. Explore the environmental attributes of renewable natural gas and biomethane programs potentially offered by CenterPoint Energy.
                                        5. Expand opportunities for district cogenerating energy systems and decarbonize existing district energy systems.
                                        6. Ease permitting requirements for locally distributed renewable energy.
                                        7. Encourage solar-friendly designs and provisions that protect solar access on commercial and residential buildings.
                                        8. Develop a City-owned renewable energy facility concept, which could serve both City and community energy needs.
                                        9. Support and incentivize use of geothermal, hydrothermal, and waste energy and heat facilities, including sewer thermal energy recovery, and other clean renewable energy alternatives in building, district, or municipal systems.
                                        10. Explore and implement carbon pricing, for example through utility franchise fees.

                                        Long-term

                                        Retrofit and design of energy efficient buildings - Continue to develop programs and strategies to retrofit buildings to be energy efficient. This includes incremental regulatory changes to advance energy efficient design and operations of buildings.(2040 Plan)

                                         

                                        Renewable and Carbon-Free Energy: Encourage the use and generation of renewable and carbon-free energy in the city. (2040 Plan Policy 69)

                                        The Minneapolis Climate Action Plan calls for increasing the use of local or directly purchased renewable energy to 10 percent of the total electricity consumed in the city by 2025.  Regulatory changes will be pursued to appropriately value renewable energy and provide incentives for its use.

                                        Xcel Energy’s projected 2021 fuel mix for the Upper Midwest includes 30 percent wind and 10 percent other renewables, expected to result from an increase in the use of wind and solar power and by offering customers additional renewable and energy-saving options. Unfortunately, the percentage of Minneapolis communitywide electricity use from local and directly purchased renewable energy has declined in recent years, but the cost of wind and solar energy is rapidly falling, and a number of alternative approaches like community solar are making renewable electricity easier to access.

                                        Ensuring that all residents and businesses can access and benefit from renewable energy and energy efficiency has many advantages. The renewable energy economy presents new job opportunities for workers currently in the manufacturing, construction and service sectors, as well as opportunities to build equity for communities that have historically been underrepresented in the energy field and marketplace.

                                        Solar Radiation Levels in Minneapolis

                                        The city of Minneapolis  has an average annual solar radiation value of 4.89 kilowatt hours per square meter per day (kWh/m2/day)

                                        Total estimated size and solar electricity production of viable roofs for Minneapolis

                                        City Gross Potential (Mwh/yr) 67,672,348

                                        Rooftop Potential (Mwh/yr) 13,956,006

                                        Gross Generation Potential (Mwh/yr)* 6,767,234

                                        Rooftop Generation Potential (Mwh/yr)* 1,395,600 (Minneapolis 2040 Comprehensive Plan)

                                                ACTION STEPS<\/h2>\n

                                                The City will seek to accomplish the following action steps to\u00a0encourage the use and generation of renewable and carbon-free energy in the city.<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\n

                                                \n
                                                  \n
                                                1. Invest in grid modernization to accommodate increases in distributed renewable energy generation.<\/li>\n
                                                2. Purchase clean energy directly through community solar gardens, contracts with renewable electricity developers, utility offerings, or by installing renewable energy systems on municipal buildings.<\/li>\n
                                                3. Continue to support and advocate for accelerated and deeper decarbonization of electricity supplied by Xcel Energy.<\/li>\n
                                                4. Explore the environmental attributes of renewable natural gas and biomethane programs potentially offered by CenterPoint Energy.<\/li>\n
                                                5. Expand opportunities for district cogenerating energy systems and decarbonize existing district energy systems.<\/li>\n
                                                6. Ease permitting requirements for locally distributed renewable energy.<\/li>\n
                                                7. Encourage solar-friendly designs and provisions that\u00a0protect solar access on commercial and residential buildings.<\/li>\n
                                                8. Develop a City-owned renewable energy facility concept, which could serve both City and community energy needs.<\/li>\n
                                                9. Support and incentivize use of geothermal, hydrothermal, and waste energy and heat facilities, including sewer thermal energy recovery, and other clean renewable energy alternatives in building, district, or municipal systems.<\/li>\n
                                                10. Explore and implement carbon pricing, for example through utility franchise fees.<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n<\/div>","__globals__":{"text_color":"globals\/colors?id=primary"}},"elements":[],"widgetType":"text-editor"}],"isInner":false},{"id":"ebb4497","elType":"container","settings":[],"elements":[{"id":"86cc64f","elType":"widget","settings":{"editor":"\n\n\n

                                                  Renewable and Carbon-Free Energy:\u00a0Encourage the use and generation of renewable and carbon-free energy in the city. (2040 Plan Policy 69)<\/span><\/h2>\n
                                                  \n

                                                  The Minneapolis Climate Action Plan calls for increasing the use of local or directly purchased renewable energy to 10 percent of the total electricity consumed in the city by 2025.\u00a0 Regulatory changes will be pursued to appropriately value renewable energy and provide incentives for its use.<\/p>\n

                                                  Xcel Energy\u2019s projected 2021 fuel mix for the Upper Midwest includes 30 percent wind and 10 percent other renewables, expected to result from an increase in the use of wind and solar power and by offering customers additional renewable and energy-saving options. Unfortunately, the percentage of Minneapolis communitywide electricity use from local and directly purchased renewable energy has declined in recent years, but the cost of wind and solar energy is rapidly falling, and a number of alternative approaches like community solar are making renewable electricity easier to access.<\/p>\n

                                                  Ensuring that all residents and businesses can access and benefit from renewable energy and energy efficiency has many advantages. The renewable energy economy presents new job opportunities for workers currently in the manufacturing, construction and service sectors, as well as opportunities to build equity for communities that have historically been underrepresented in the energy field and marketplace.<\/p>\n<\/div>","__globals__":{"text_color":"globals\/colors?id=primary"}},"elements":[],"widgetType":"text-editor"}],"isInner":false},{"id":"4e4584d","elType":"container","settings":{"flex_direction":"row","flex_wrap":"wrap","flex_gap":{"unit":"px","size":0},"border_border":"solid","shape_divider_top":"waves-pattern","shape_divider_top_color":"#949797","margin":{"unit":"px","top":"-11","right":"0","bottom":"0","left":"0","isLinked":false},"padding":{"unit":"px","top":"42","right":"0","bottom":"44","left":"0","isLinked":false},"__globals__":{"shape_divider_top_color":"","border_color":"globals\/colors?id=secondary"}},"elements":[{"id":"5a2d905","elType":"container","settings":{"flex_direction":"column","content_width":"full","width":{"unit":"%","size":"33.3333"},"flex_justify_content":"center","flex_align_items":"center","background_background":"classic","background_overlay_background":"classic","border_border":"solid","border_width":{"unit":"px","top":"1","right":"1","bottom":"1","left":"1","isLinked":true},"border_color":"#898888","border_radius":{"unit":"px","top":"5","right":"5","bottom":"5","left":"5","isLinked":true},"margin":{"unit":"px","top":"0","right":"0","bottom":"7","left":"0","isLinked":false},"__globals__":{"background_overlay_color":"globals\/colors?id=f2dcafc","background_color":"globals\/colors?id=f2dcafc"}},"elements":[{"id":"45f502a","elType":"widget","settings":{"editor":"
